$i+1=2 \\\\implies i=1$. $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\text{ XOR } q[0]$. \\n   $i+1=1 \\\\implies i=0$. This doesn\'t work for $q_{next}[0]$. \\n   Actually, the tap at 1 means $q[0]$ is the tap. In Galois, the feedback $q[0]$ is XORed into the tap positions. \\n   If the taps are 32, 22, 2, 1: \\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$; \\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\text{ XOR } (32? q[0] : 0)$; \\n   $q_{next}[21] = q[22] \\text{ XOR } (22? q[0] : 0)$; \\n   Wait, let\'s use the index $i$ directly. \\n   If tap is at position $P$, then $q[P-1]$ is XORed. \\n   Taps: $P=32, 22, 2, 1$. \\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$; \\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\text{ XOR } (32 \\text{ is tap} ? q[0] : 0)$; \\n   $q_{next}[20] = q[21] \\text{ XOR } (22 \\text{ is tap} ? q[0] : 0)$; \\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\text{ XOR } (2 \\text{ is tap} ? q[0] : 0)$; \\n   And the tap at 1? If $P=1$, then $q[0]$ is XORed. But $q[0]$ is the feedback. \\n   In many Galois LFSRs, $q[0]$ is XORed with the tap positions, and the result is shifted. \\n   Let\'s try: \\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$; \\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\text{ XOR } (32 \\text{ is tap} ? q[0] : 0)$; \\n   $q_{next}[20] = q[21] \\text{ XOR } (22 \\text{ is tap} ? q[0] : 0)$; \\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\text{ XOR } (2 \\text{ is tap} ? q[0] : 0)$; \\n   Wait, if $P=1$ is a tap, $q[0]$ is the tap. $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\text{ XOR } q[0]$. This is already covered by $P=2$? No. \\n   Let\'s assume the taps are the indices $i$ where $q[i]$ is XORed with $q[0]$ to produce $q[i-1]$. \\n   Taps: 32 (index 31), 22 (index 21), 2 (index 1), 1 (index 0). \\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\text{ XOR } q[0]$; \\n   $q_{next}[20] = q[21] \\text{ XOR } q[0]$; \\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\text{ XOR } q[0]$; \\n   $q_{next}[-1]$... this still doesn\'t work. \\n   Let\'s rethink. A 32-bit register has indices 31 to 0. \\n   If the taps are 32, 22, 2, 1, these are the bit positions. \\n   Position 32 is index 31. \\n   Position 22 is index 21. \\n   Position 2 is index 1. \\n   Positi