n<module_interface>\nmodule TopModule (\n    input  logic clk,\n    input  logic reset,\n    output logic [31:0] q\n);\n\n</module_interface>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.ASSISTANT: 'assistant'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{\n    "reasoning": "1. The requirement is to implement a 32-bit Galois LFSR. In a Galois LFSR, the register shifts, and the LSB (q[0]) is XORed into specific \'tap\' positions.\\n2. The taps are specified at bit positions 32, 22, 2, and 1. In a 0-indexed 32-bit register (q[31:0]), bit position 32 corresponds to the bit being shifted out (or the position that would be index 32 if it were 1-indexed). However, typically in a 32-bit LFSR, \'bit 32\' refers to the bit that is shifted out of the register. Since the register is q[31:0], the bit being shifted out is q[0]. The instruction says \'bit positions 32, 22, 2, and 1\'. In 1-based indexing for a 32-bit register, bit 32 is q[31], bit 22 is q[21], bit 2 is q[1], and bit 1 is q[0]. But the spec says \'a bit position with a tap is XORed with the LSB output bit (q[0]) to produce its next value\'. This implies that if we are at bit $i$, the new value is $q[i] \\u2235 q[0]$ if $i$ is a tap position. Let\'s look at the taps: 32, 22, 2, 1. Since the register is 32 bits (indices 0 to 31), position 32 is usually the \'feedback\' bit (the one shifting out). However, the spec says \'a bit position with a tap is XORed with q[0]\'. For a 32-bit register, the bit positions are 1 to 32. Position 32 $\\\\rightarrow$ index 31, Position 22 $\\\\rightarrow$ index 21, Position 2 $\\\\rightarrow$ index 1, Position 1 $\\\\rightarrow$ index 0. Wait, if position 1 is a tap, then $q[0]_{next} = q[0] \\u2235 q[0] = 0$? No, that doesn\'t make sense for an LFSR. Let\'s re-read: \'a bit position with a tap is XORed with the LSB output bit (q[0]) to produce its next value\'. In a Galois LFSR, the feedback bit (the bit shifted out) is XORed with the bits at the tap positions. For a 32-bit register, the bit being shifted out is q[0]. So, the next state of the register $q_{next}$ is: $q_{next}[i-1] = q[i]$ for non-tap positions, and $q_{next}[i-1] = q[i] \\u2235 q[0]$ for tap positions. \\n3. Let\'s map the taps: Position 32 $\\\\rightarrow$ index 31. Position 22 $\\\\rightarrow$ index 21. Position 2 $\\\\rightarrow$ index 1. Position 1 $\\\\rightarrow$ index 0. If position 1 is a tap, then $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$? No, shifting right means $q[i]$ moves to $q[i-1]$. So $q_{next}[0] = q[1]$. The taps are applied to the bits that *receive* the bit being shifted out. In a right-shifting Galois LFSR, the bit $q[0]$ is XORed into the tap positions. The tap positions are 32, 22, 2, 1. If we shift right, the bit at index $i$ moves to $i-1$. The bit $q[0]$ is the feedback. The taps are indices where $q[i] = q[i] \\u2235 q[0]$. Wait, the standard definition: $q_{next}[i-1] = q[i]$ (for $i > 0$), and $q_{next}[i-1] = q[i] \\u2235 q[0]$ if $i$ is a tap. If the tap is at position 1 (index 0), then $q_{next}[0]$ is part of the shift? No, position 1 is index 0. Position 2 is index 1. Position 22 is index 21. Position 32 is index 31. \\n4. Let\'s refine the logic: In a Galois LFSR shifting right, $q[i]$ moves to $q[i-1]$. The feedback bit is $q[0]$. The taps are positions $i$ where $q[i] = q[i] \\u2235 q[0]$. For a 32-bit register, the indices are 0 to 31. The shift is $q[i] \\\\rightarrow q[i-1]$. The bit $q[0]$ is the feedback. The taps are applied to the bits *after* the shift. So, $q_{next}[0] = q[1]$ (if 1 is not a tap), or $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 1 is a tap). But the spec says position 1 is a tap. If position 1 is index 0, then $q_{next}[0]$ is the result of the XOR. \\n5. Let\'s follow the most standard implementation for these specific tap values (which are common for 32-bit LFSRs): The feedback is $q[0]$. The bits at the tap positions are XORed with $q[0]$. The taps are 32, 22, 2, 1. In 0-indexing: index 31, 21, 1, 0. If we shift