\\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$ (The feedback is shifted into the MSB).\\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\u2235 q[0]$ if 32 is a tap? No, position 32 is index 31. \\n   Let\'s use the standard Galois logic: $q_{next}[i-1] = q[i] \\u2235 (q[0] \\text{ if } i \\text{ is a tap else } 0)$. \\n   Wait, the spec says: \'a bit position with a tap is XORed with the LSB output bit (q[0]) to produce its next value\'. This means if $i$ is a tap, $q[i]_{next} = q[i] \\u2235 q[0]$. This is a parallel update, not a shift. But it says \'shifts right\'. \\n   Correct interpretation of Galois LFSR (Right Shift): \\n   $q_{next}[i-1] = q[i] \\u2235 (q[0] \\text{ if } i \\text{ is a tap else } 0)$ for $i=1 \\u2235 31$. \\n   And $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$. \\n   Let\'s check the taps: 32, 22, 2, 1. \\n   If index $i$ is a tap (where $i = \\text{pos}-1$), then $q[i]$ is XORed with $q[0]$ to produce the next value at $q[i-1]$. \\n   So: \\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 32 is a tap) \\n   $q_{next}[20] = q[21] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 22 is a tap) \\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 2 is a tap) \\n   And for position 1 (index 0), $q_{next}[0]$ is already defined? No, position 1 is index 0. If 1 is a tap, $q[0]$ is XORed with $q[0]$ to produce... what? $q_{next}[-1]$? No. \\n   Let\'s look at the taps again: 32, 22, 2, 1. These are the bits that are XORed with the feedback. \\n   In a 32-bit LFSR, the bits are $q[31 \\u2235 0]$. The taps are usually indices. \\n   If the taps are 32, 22, 2, 1, then the bits $q[31], q[21], q[1], q[0]$ are the ones involved. \\n   In a Galois LFSR, the feedback $q[0]$ is XORed with the tap bits. \\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$ (this is the shift-in)\\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 32 is a tap)\\n   $q_{next}[20] = q[21] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 22 is a tap)\\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 2 is a tap)\\n   What about tap 1? If position 1 (index 0) is a tap, then $q[0]$ is XORed with $q[0]$? That doesn\'t affect the shift. \\n   Wait, in a right-shifting Galois LFSR, the feedback is $q[0]$. The tap positions are the bits that $q[0]$ is XORed into. \\n   The bit $q[0]$ is XORed into $q[31], q[21], q[1], q[0]$. \\n   So: \\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$ \\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 32 is a tap) \\n   $q_{next}[20] = q[21] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 22 is a tap) \\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 2 is a tap) \\n   And $q[0]$ itself? $q_{next}[0]$ is the bit that comes from $q[1]$. \\n   If position 1 is a tap, then $q[0]$ is XORed with $q[0]$? No, the tap position is where the XOR happens. \\n   If position 1 is a tap, $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$. \\n   This covers all bits: $q[31]$ is the new bit, $q[30 \\u2235 0]$ are the shifted bits. \\n   Let\'s re-verify: \\n   Taps: 32, 22, 2, 1. \\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$ \\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\u2235 q[0]$ (32 is tap) \\n   $q_{next}[20] = q[21] \\u2235 q[0]$ (22 is tap) \\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$ (2 is tap, and 1 is a tap? If 1 is a tap, $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$). \\n   Actually, the tap at position 1 (index 0) would mean $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$? No, the tap is at $q[0]$, so $q[0]$ is XORed with $q[0]$. That\'s just 0. \\n   Wait, the standard 32-bit Galois LFSR taps are 32, 22, 2, 1 (using 1-based indexing). \\n   This means: $q_{next}[i-1] = q[i] \\u2235 (q[0] \\text{ if } i \\text{ is a tap})$. \\n   For $i=32: q_{next}[31] = q[0]$ (Wait, if 32 is a tap, $q_{next}[31] = q[0] \\u2235 q[0] = 0$?) No. \\n   Let\'s use the logic: The bit $q[0]$ is XORed into the tap bits. \\n   The tap bits are $q[31], q[21], q[1], q[0]$. \\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$ \\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\u2235 q[0]$ (since 32 is a tap) \\n   $q_{next}[20] = q[21] \\u2235 q[0]$ (since 22 is a tap) \\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$ (since 2 is a tap) \\n   And if 1 is a tap, $q[0]$ is XORed with $q[0]$... this is confusing. \\n   Let\'s look at it another way: A Galois LFSR is defined by the polynomial. For 32-bit, the taps are often given as the indices of the bits that are XORed with the feedback. \\n   If the taps are 32, 22, 2, 1, then $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$, $q_{next}[21] = q[22] \\u2235 q[0]$, $q_{next}[1] = q[2] \\u2235 q[0]$, $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$. \\n   Wait, the instruction says: \'a bit position with a tap is XORed with the LSB output bit (q[0]) to produce its next value, while bit positions without a tap shift right unchanged\'. \\n   This means for each bit $i$: \\n   If $i$ is a tap: $q_{next}[i] = q[i] \\u2235 q[0]$ (but this doesn\'t include a shift). \\n   The only way \'shift right\' and \'tap XORed with q[0]\' work together is: \\n   $q_{next}[i-1] = q[i] \\u2235 (q[0] \\text{ if } i \\text{ is a tap else } 0)$ \\n   And $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$ (to complete the shift). \\n   Let\'s check the taps: 32, 22, 2, 1. \\n   $i=32 \\rightarrow q_{next}[31] = q[0] \\u2235 q[0] = 0$. This can\'t be right. \\n   Let\'s try the other interpretation: The tap position is the bit that is XORed with $q[0]$ to *become* the next value of that bit. \\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[31] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 32 is tap) \\n   $q_{next}[21] = q[21] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 22 is tap) \\n   $q_{next}[1] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 2 is tap) \\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[0] \\u2235 q[0]$ (if 1 is tap) \\n   And then shift everything? No. \\n   Let\'s go back to basics. Galois LFSR: $q_{next} = (q \\text{ shifted right}) \\u2235 (q[0] \\text{ at tap positions})$. \\n   In a 32-bit register $q[31:0]$, shifting right means $q[i] \\rightarrow q[i-1]$. \\n   $q_{next}[0] = q[1]$ \\n   $q_{next}[1] = q[2] \\u2235 (q[0] \\text{ if 2 is a tap})$ \\n   $q_{next}[21] = q[22] \\u2235 (q[0] \\text{ if 22 is a tap})$ \\n   $q_{next}[30] = q[31] \\u2235 (q[0] \\text{ if 32 is a tap})$ \\n   $q_{next}[31] = q[0]$ (the bit being shifted out). \\n   What about tap 1? If 1 is a tap, then $q_{next}[0] = q[1] \\u2235 q[0]$. \\n   This covers all bits. Let\'s check the taps: 32, 22, 2, 1. \\n   Indices for $q[i]$ that are taps: 31, 21, 1, 0.